	<article>

		<header>
			
			<h1>The importance of policy coherence in Fisheries Partnership Agreements </h1>

			
			<h4>
												30 October 2010
										</h4>

					</header>


		
		
					<p>As the Common Fisheries Policy (CFP) of the EU is due to be reformed in 2013, <i>Fair Politics</i> urges the EC and the Parliament to take a closer look at FPAs and their implications for developing countries. In its efforts to realise the ‘Millennium Development Goals’ the EU made policy coherence for development (PCD) a central pillar, and concerning FPAs, its development policy explicitly commits the EU to paying particular attention to the development objectives of the countries with which the EU has made or will make fisheries agreements.</p><p><i>Fair Politics</i> highlights however that there are no effective legal arrangements for the EU or its member states to prohibit businesses from running their own operations in countries outside of EU FPAs, and it is probable that private agreements would replace FPAs if these were ended. If this were to happen, transparency and public control would be even less likely, so it cannot be denied that fisheries agreements are important and should stay in place. But with the reform of the CFP, some fundamental changes need to be made in order for the agreements to be satisfactory for all stakeholders, most importantly for small-scale fisheries in developing countries that are so important in combating poverty. </p><p>In order to improve PCD in FPAs, <i>Fair Politics</i> makes a series of recommendations, including: </p>
<ul>

<li>conditions and prioritisation needs to be introduced for access to third-country waters. In line with the FAO code of conduct, priority access should be reserved for national fleets, especially small-scale and artisanal fishing activities. Further access should be restricted to those operators who can demonstrate that their operations fit with the EU’s criteria for sustainable fisheries development; </li>

<li>the EU should respect the surplus principle as included in the UN Convention on the Law of the Sea (UNCLOS); it should not fish in countries where a surplus is not proved and the prevention of overexploitation cannot be guaranteed; </li>

<li>the EU should step up efforts and provide the necessary resources to help contracting countries develop more effective national resource management systems in order to prevent overexploitation; </li>

<li>the EU should ensure better adherence to laws and codes of conduct by EU fleets; </li>

<li>fisheries agreements must be negotiated, concluded or extended based on a scientific basis and reliable data. </li>

</ul>

		
		
				<div class="box related">
			<h3>Sources</h3>
			
<p><i>Fair Politics</i>, Case study, ‘Fisheries Partnership Agreements’, August 2010</p><p>
<a href="http://www.fairpolitics.nl/europa/cases/fisheries_partnership_agreements" target="_self">http://www.fairpolitics.nl/europa/cases/fisheries_partnership_agreements</a></p>		</div>
		
		
				<div class="box">
			<h3>Editorial comment</h3>
			<p>It is vital, though difficult, to improve policy coherence for development in the reform of the CFP’s external dimension , where a number of aspects of EU fisheries relations with ACP countries need to be considered, including access to resources, trade – access to markets, SPS -, and development cooperation. The recommendations proposed should be looked into, particularly the proposal to introduce conditionalities for EU fleet access to ACP waters. However, the paper does not address two key aspects that will greatly influence how much PCD can become a successful tool for combating poverty in ACP countries. Firstly, it is necessary to look at how these future relations can be conducive to fair, transparent and sustainable fish trade. Secondly, it is necessary to have a coherent approach in bilateral relations and in international fora. In terms of combating poverty, the fact that the EU, and EU fleets, would, for example, take the scientific advice as basis for access negotiations would be of little help if the EU cannot, in international fora, convince all stakeholders, including other distant-water fishing nations, to adopt the same approach.</p>
		</div>
		
		<div class="clear"></div>

		
